commits.commitMessage:
Publish events to another RabbitMQ host

Provide a way for git-sync to publish events, which are typically
sourced from a Gerrit service.

Resolves: FARM-322
Change-Id: Ibbb3470be0eadf847f96ea906e9307df4fec9afa
commits.subject: Publish events to another RabbitMQ host

comments.message:
That looks quite disorganized, instead maybe create a dedicated section such as:

publishers:
  - type: 'rabbitmq'
    host; 'mirror-host'
    exchange: 'mirror_exchange'
    username: 'guest'
    password: 'guest'

That way it's way more open.

You're not really documenting the publishing mechanism.

I would expect a section such as 'Events publishing' that documents the publish process and available implementations (rabbitmq for now).

If you have an object RabbitMQPublisher that you start initially (in the configuration) and you add to a list of publishers, you can reduce this code to

  publishers.each { |p| p.publish(event) }
That should be still shown even if there is a publisher.
Cf previous, shouldn't be any need to change anything in this file. Except maybe to receive a list of publishers.
Mostly the same, no need for all this.
I don't see the need for this?
In the old design, work() could publish events that don't require sync.  In the current design only events require sync are in the event queue, and therefore it's no longer needed.

You need to pop all the events available before the sync, otherwise the following can happen:

:state_0
event = remote system is :state_1
start_sync
... at the same time, new event that remote system is now in :state_2, event is queued
end_sync => local system is in :state_1
publishing all available events, so :state_1 and :state_2
Use a close for all that.
These attributes do not need to be modified anymore
Establish the connection once when the class is initialized so that you can reuse the connection.
You could remove all the @should_resync stuff now and replace that test by a @event_queue.empty? test
I guess it doesn't hurt to pass publishers.  I didn't because it doesn't apply to this case.
host, port, username and password are already used by gerrit base class.
host and rabbitmq_host are meant to be different, same for the others.
Patch Set 2: Commit message was updated.
Change has been successfully merged by Bertrand Roussel

commits.commitMessage:
Do not block all threads in case of long sync

If there is a long sync going on and multiple events are
coming, it will eventually take all threads while only one is working.

This should avoid to occupy all threads by simply flagging
that it should redo a sync, even if it thinks the work is done.
